 that American poetics has taken for the past two centuries. As an idea of poetry based on genres of poems such as ballads, elegies, odes, hymns, drinking songs, and epistles gave way to an idea of poetry based on genres of people—Black, White, male, female, Indigenous—almost all poetry became lyric poetry. Jackson traces the twisted paths leading to our current understanding of lyric, along the way presenting not only a new history but a new theory of American poetry.A major reassessment of the origins and development of American poetics, Before Modernism argues against a literary critical narrative that links American modernism directly to British or European Romanticism, emphasizing instead the many ways in which early Black poets intervened by inventing what Wheatley called “the deep design” of American lyric.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAmerican poetryxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLyric poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoeticsxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAdult.  aAll things.  aAnalogy.  aArchive.  aBiography.  aBlack people.  aBook History (journal).  aC. L. R. James.  aClotel.  aColony.  aColumbia University Press.  aComplexion.  aCoviello.  aCritical race theory.  aDesertification.  aDramatic monologue.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aEnglish poetry.  aEvocation.  aFirst appearance.  aFrigate.  aFugitive slave laws.  aGenre.  aGeoffrey Hartman.  aGeorgics.  aGreat books.  aHarlem Renaissance.  aHenry Kissinger.  aHenry Wadsworth Longfellow.  aHeptameter.  aHigh culture.  aHistoricism.  aHistory.  aHolism.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIdealization.  aIdeology